ate fiscal incentives are counterproductive, and competition among public and choice schools is difficult to discern. They conclude that school choice could succeed if certain conditions were met, and they offer guidelines to strengthen accountability and repair the voucher system.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jul 2019) 0aEducational accountabilityzWisconsinzMilwaukeevCase studies. 0aSchool choicezWisconsinzMilwaukeevCase studies. 7aEDUCATION / Experimental Methods.2bisacsh1 aDickman, Anneliese M., eauthor.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066772108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013z978311053799440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300127973423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300127973.jpg  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066772-1  YUP eBook-Package 2000-2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aEBA_FAO